What is an UNT?|
PG| ***** 127 ***** |


AT| In general an immediate overcall of 2NT after an Opponent opens either a major or a minor is an Unusual NT - UNT.|
PG| ***** 128 ***** |


AT| I like the definition in Bridge Guys web site |CP|1|AT|^*Hwww.bridgeguys.com/Conventions/UnusualNoTrump.html^*N|CP||AT|,  "The Unusual No Trump is a conventional defense method designed to show two suited hands in competitive situations with one bid."|
PG| ***** 129 ***** |


AT| The bid always shows the two lower unbid suits - at least five cards in each suit. Therefore, after one of a majors opening it always shows the |cp|1|at|two minors|cp||at|. And after a minor opening it shows |cp|1|at|hearts and the other minor|cp||at|. Let's look at the four possible UNT bids by partner sitting North:|
pg| ***** 130 ***** |


HT|m|va|6|at|^B{|ia|1s2np|at|}|HT|p|va|6|fp|2|at|^B North has five Clubs and five Diamonds. |
PG| ***** 131 ***** |


ht|m|va|6|at|^n{|ia|1h2np|at|}|HT|p|va|6|at|^N North has five Clubs and five Diamonds.|
PG| ***** 132 ***** |


HT|r|at|^B{|ia|1d2np|at|}|HT|t|va|6|at|
^B North has five Clubs and five Hearts. |
PG| ***** 133 ***** |


HT|r|AT|^N{|ia|1c2np|at|}|HT|t|Va|6|at|
^N North has five Diamonds and five Hearts.|
PG| ***** 134 ***** |


fp||at|

Can we bid UNT holding a two suited hand with one as spades?|
PG| ***** 135 ***** |


AT| Negative.|
pg| ***** 136 ***** |


